The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 24, 2004 				 Bharti bottomline swells to Rs 296 cr
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Mittal: Music to the ears																								New Delhi, July 23: Bharti Tele-Ventures net profit has jumped 855 per cent to Rs 296 crore in the first quarter compared with Rs 31 crore in the previous corresponding period.																								Consolidated revenues grew 65 per cent to Rs 1,705 crore over the corresponding quarter of 2003-04 when it stood at Rs 1,036 crore. EBITDA (earnings before depreciation, pre-operating costs, amortisation, interest and taxation) increased to Rs 620 crore from Rs 289 crore for the corresponding quarter of last year, an increase of 115 per cent.																								BTVLs cash profit from operations grew 140 per cent to Rs 541 crore compared with Rs 226 crore in the corresponding previous quarter. The company said that the growth is a result of operational as well as financial efficiencies achieved by them. 																								Chairman and group managing director Sunil Mittal said, BTVLs strong performance during the first quarter has once again demonstrated its ability to maximise the full benefits of scale and size. We are now getting ready for our next leap, when we roll out our telecom services in new circles. quot;																								The net debt to annualised EBITDA ratio was 1.54 times.																								Bharti had approximately 76.7 lakh mobile and over 7 lakh fixed line customers, as of June 30, 2004, an increase in the total customer base of more than 100 per cent, over the corresponding period last year. 																								Bhartis share of net additions of all-India GSM mobile customers was 29.6 per cent and that of all-India wireless customers was 22.8 per cent. Bharti maintained its leadership position and its market share of all-India GSM mobile customers at 26.3 per cent.																								The company will float a sponsored ADR secondary offering of a maximum of 200 million shares. It today sought shareholders approval to offload the shares. 																								The offering will be made according to the governments guidelines, which allow the company to sponsor an ADR offering of shares to be sold by the companys shareholders. 																								Bharti is likely to file a registration statement with the US Securities and Exchange Commission during the second quarter.
